          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 4735,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "October 2025",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s2",
          "section_path": [
            "Coalition for Open Digital Ecosystems",
            "1. Introduction"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 2,
          "char_len": 12
        }
      },
      {
        "para_id": "p13",
        "items": [],
        "meta": {
          "skipped": false,
          "skip_reason": null,
          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 9711,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "In CODE's view, the solution to the challenges consumers face can be exhaustively resolved from effective enforcement by the Commission of existing tools. Many of the challenges identified by the Commission in its Call for Evidence can be addressed through existing consumer protection and competition laws. For example, the UCPD, DSA, DMA, AI Act, Data Act and the GDPR contain relevant provisions. As a result, CODE does not advocate in favor of new legislation in this area, but rather a more coherent, coordinated and exhaustive enforcement of existing EU laws against the challenges identified by the Commission in its Call for Evidence.",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s3",
          "section_path": [
            "2. Recommendations for embedding consumer choice"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 102,
          "char_len": 642
        }
      },
      {
        "para_id": "p14",
        "items": [],
        "meta": {
          "skipped": false,
          "skip_reason": null,
          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 4288,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "In light of this, CODE invites policymakers to carefully consider the digital fairness initiative in light of the EU simplification agenda by taking into account existing frameworks and enforcement mechanisms, to avoid legal complexity, regulatory overlap, or added burdens on traders - while ensuring a stable, innovation-friendly business environment that enables consumers to fully benefit from the single market.",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s3",
          "section_path": [
            "2. Recommendations for embedding consumer choice"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 58,
          "char_len": 416
        }
      },
      {
        "para_id": "p15",
        "items": [],
        "meta": {
          "skipped": false,
          "skip_reason": null,
          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 3379,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "Having this in mind, we encourage the Commission to guide its actions by the following principles when considering how to achieve \"digital fairness\", preserving choice and protection for Europe's consumers:",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s3",
          "section_path": [
            "2. Recommendations for embedding consumer choice"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 30,
          "char_len": 206
        }
      },
      {
        "para_id": "p16",
        "items": [
          {
            "topic": "Design Patterns",
            "topic_source": "dfa",
            "evidence_quotes": [
              {
                "quote": "without unnecessary obstruction or interference from the platform controller"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "meta": {
          "skipped": false,
          "skip_reason": null,
          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 10337,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "Consumers must be able to select, use and retain their preferred browsers, search engines, messaging and video apps, voice assistants and payment services, without unnecessary obstruction or interference from the platform controller insofar as those services are available and widely used on a given device.",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s4",
          "section_path": [
            "2.1 Freedom to set and retain preferred defaults"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 45,
          "char_len": 307
        }
      },
      {
        "para_id": "p17",
        "items": [
          {
            "topic": "Design Patterns",
            "topic_source": "dfa",
            "evidence_quotes": [
              {
                "quote": "platforms must not exploit this position to interfere with users' intention to use a different service."
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "meta": {
          "skipped": false,
          "skip_reason": null,
          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 9229,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "While preinstallation of services is common and benefits OEMs, developers and consumers, platforms must not exploit this position to interfere with users' intention to use a different service.",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s4",
          "section_path": [
            "2.1 Freedom to set and retain preferred defaults"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 28,
          "char_len": 192
        }
      },
      {
        "para_id": "p18",
        "items": [
          {
            "topic": "Design Patterns",
            "topic_source": "dfa",
            "evidence_quotes": [
              {
                "quote": "Design patterns that hinder switching"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "meta": {
          "skipped": false,
          "skip_reason": null,
          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 8475,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "Design patterns that hinder switching - such as nesting key settings deep in menus, excessive or misleading pop-ups, requiring multiple confirmations, or resetting preferences post-update - must be treated as manipulative and anti-competitive.",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s4",
          "section_path": [
            "2.1 Freedom to set and retain preferred defaults"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 31,
          "char_len": 243
        }
      },
      {
        "para_id": "p19",
        "items": [
          {
            "topic": "Design Patterns",
            "topic_source": "dfa",
            "evidence_quotes": [
              {
                "quote": "prompt the user to switch a given default"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "meta": {
          "skipped": false,
          "skip_reason": null,
          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 9268,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "Third-party developers should be given access to the system-level APIs necessary to offer competitive alternatives, particularly in instances where the owner of an operating system can themselves prompt the user to switch a given default, while ensuring users' security and maintaining their privacy.",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s4",
          "section_path": [
            "2.1 Freedom to set and retain preferred defaults"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 43,
          "char_len": 300
        }
      },
      {
        "para_id": "p20",
        "items": [],
        "meta": {
          "skipped": false,
          "skip_reason": null,
          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 5787,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "The technology-neutral design of most legal safeguards ensures that existing consumer laws can evolve with the digital environment, provided that more effective, timely and streamlined enforcement keeps pace with innovation and that there is strong coordination between regulatory bodies within the EU.",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s4",
          "section_path": [
            "2.1 Freedom to set and retain preferred defaults"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 42,
          "char_len": 302
        }
      },
      {
        "para_id": "p21",
        "items": [],
        "meta": {
